column38: not that comes to mind. the system works, I take payments and you pass the money onto me. The time delay before receiving funds is acceptable and understandable (clearing from banks and card providers). Having to leave funds in the account to cover refunds on days where there have been few sales is annoying, but again understandable to cover yourself from losses if people go out of business. As in the case of the Cash Advance loans, perhaps once a customer has built up a history with you, you permit refunds over the retained funds value. For example I leave £400 in the account, enough to cover most goods yet some of my goods are valued at over £1000. If a customer wanted a refund for those, not only would I cry, but the customer would have to wait until I'd built up £1000 of credit in the account - which isn't good customer service - or I'd have to pay them through bank transfer and make a loss on the card fees from the initial sale. The instructions for handling refunds weren't very clear, so on my first refund (I may have had only 1 or 2), I had no money in the account so had to refund them in card rather than back onto the card. You have offered me a Cash Advance, so you must trust me to repay, so couldn't that same trust enable me to refund a transaction for an amount greater than the funds you retain?

My card reader struggles to pair via Bluetooth to the app. Customers have been waiting fir as long as 5 mins before they connect. Also, once app is open, would be handy if the phone didn't go into sleep mode. This automatically loses Bluetooth connection with reader. Should stay awake like when using Google maps for eg. And no, I'm not going into settings each time I use the app, to stop phone from sleeping, and then resetting it once I've used the app.

I would like to be able to have an option to sometimes switch to receive deposits weekly on a set day instead of daily. I managed to take a few payments only during that time, having to get my clients to pay by cash or BACS. When you finally replied, the steps advised did not work. We were told to unpair the card reader but the instructions to do this seemed incorrect. In the end, we uninstalled the app and reinstalled it, which seems to have sorted the problem.
My impression is that it is a great payment system but if anything goes wrong, the customer support is woeful.

column37: Occasionally I am taking a payment and I get a message to say the card reader has failed - I get a big red circle with a cross in it.  I then retry and the client has been charged twice.  Another occasion when I got this message I abandoned taking payment and the client did a bank transfer later that day.  The client contacted me to say that the card reader payment had shown up on their bank statement.  I later found that this is temporary situation where the bank holds the money in reserve and it is later cleared.  I've noticed that when there is a failed transaction the payment is sitting in the basket.  I think I may have resolved the issue because from now on I make sure that I use the transaction in the basket rather than putting the transaction through again, to avoid charging twice.  Anyway, I just wanted to let you know that when users get a big red circle with a cross in it to say transaction has failed it is a bit confusing as to what to do about it.  Particularly when the client is sitting in from of me expecting to be able to leave the session - I'm a psychotherapist.
column38: Perhaps a message on the card reader to tell user what to do if there is a failed transaction.  For example, please got to basket, select transaction and start again.  Do not put in another payment transaction or you will charge the client twice.
